in the self-help industry.

00:01:07.040 --> 00:01:09.710
And he documented
that in "10% Happier."

00:01:09.710 --> 00:01:12.680
And what's really
amazing about that book,

00:01:12.680 --> 00:01:16.100
as opposed to a lot of
other self-help books,

00:01:16.100 --> 00:01:20.630
it's not immediately
embracing of everything

00:01:20.630 --> 00:01:25.400
that's New Agey and self-helpy.

00:01:25.400 --> 00:01:27.590
He comes in, as
he calls himself,

00:01:27.590 --> 00:01:29.390
a hard-charging skeptic.

00:01:29.390 --> 00:01:33.580
And he kind of sifts the
substance from the snake oil.

00:01:33.580 --> 00:01:37.160
And it's written not in a
proselytizing or pedantic way.

00:01:37.160 --> 00:01:40.040
It's written in a way that
you can really identify with.

00:01:40.040 --> 00:01:42.710
So I definitely recommend
checking that out.

00:01:42.710 --> 00:01:45.380
And then he follows up with
"Meditation for Fidgety

00:01:45.380 --> 00:01:48.140
Skeptics," which is--

00:01:48.140 --> 00:01:53.090
if "10% Happier" gets you bought
into meditating to begin with,

00:01:53.090 --> 00:01:55.130
this book is kind of the how-to.

00:01:55.130 --> 00:01:59.450
If you have a lot of objections
and maybe aren't fully

00:01:59.450 --> 00:02:01.156
bought in, then it is helpful.

00:02:01.156 --> 00:02:03.530
Or then you are bought in,
and you do think it's helpful,

00:02:03.530 --> 00:02:06.680
but you're having a hard
time just doing it every day,

00:02:06.680 --> 00:02:09.259
this book is going
to help you there.

00:02:09.259 --> 00:02:11.360
So I recommend both.

00:02:11.360 --> 00:02:14.405
He has a podcast as well,
"10% Happier" podcast.

00:02:14.405 --> 00:02:15.740
He has an app.

00:02:15.740 --> 00:02:18.890
And he's still doing all of
the amazing journalistic things

00:02:18.890 --> 00:02:23.350
as well on "GMA"
and other platforms.

00:02:23.350 --> 00:02:26.020
So yeah, thank you so
much, Dan, for coming here.

00:02:26.020 --> 00:02:26.120
DAN HARRIS: Thank you.

00:02:26.120 --> 00:02:27.070
SPEAKER: We really
appreciate it.

00:02:27.070 --> 00:02:27.440
DAN HARRIS: Thank you.

00:02:27.440 --> 00:02:29.510
I love from an anthropological
standpoint that--

00:02:29.510 --> 00:02:30.950
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:30.950 --> 00:02:32.870
Oh, hi.

00:02:32.870 --> 00:02:35.400
Nobody sits right-- except
for this brave individual.

00:02:35.400 --> 00:02:38.810
It's like there's some
sort of force field.

00:02:38.810 --> 00:02:41.810
SPEAKER: Maybe they're
just afraid of meditation.

00:02:41.810 --> 00:02:42.884
DAN HARRIS: Or just me.

00:02:42.884 --> 00:02:44.780
SPEAKER: (LAUGHING) Yeah.

00:02:44.780 --> 00:02:48.350
So I want to kind of set
some context here and just

00:02:48.350 --> 00:02:53.150
talk about your life
pre-meditation and your outlook

00:02:53.150 --> 00:02:54.250
on life.

00:02:54.250 --> 00:02:57.160
I think your dad actually had
an interesting phrase that

00:02:57.160 --> 00:03:01.130
[INAUDIBLE] that kind of
represented your take on life

00:03:01.130 --> 00:03:03.140
and just being a very
ambitious person trying

00:03:03.140 --> 00:03:04.090
to make it to the top.

00:03:04.090 --> 00:03:05.506
It was something
about insecurity.

00:03:05.506 --> 00:03:07.880
And then post-meditation,
just so we kind of

00:03:07.880 --> 00:03:10.030
get people bought into
your transformation.

00:03:10.030 --> 00:03:11.340
Yeah.

00:03:11.340 --> 00:03:12.980
DAN HARRIS: So I was--

00:03:12.980 --> 00:03:17.210
my dad is an academic
physician, a recently retired

00:03:17.210 --> 00:03:20.480
academic physician
in Boston and very--

00:03:20.480 --> 00:03:25.240
both my parents are
academic physicians,

00:03:25.240 --> 00:03:29.430
so really sort of hard charging,
secular folks in Boston.

00:03:29.430 --> 00:03:32.750
And my dad had an expression,
which is, the price of security

00:03:32.750 --> 00:03:37.910
is insecurity, which is a
great thing to tell your child.

00:03:37.910 --> 00:03:40.260
It always shocks
people when I tell them

00:03:40.260 --> 00:03:43.280
that my father's Jewish.

00:03:43.280 --> 00:03:48.050
And so it was this kind of idea
that the only way to succeed

00:03:48.050 --> 00:03:49.550
is to work incredibly hard.

00:03:49.550 --> 00:03:51.920
And it takes a lot
of gnashing of teeth

00:03:51.920 --> 00:03:53.450
and rending of garments.

00:03:53.450 --> 00:04:01.640
And so that became my way
of surviving when I arrived

00:04:01.640 --> 00:04:06.220
at ABC News in the year 2000.

00:04:06.220 --> 00:04:08.570
And I was 28 and really
young and insecure

00:04:08.570 --> 00:04:11.870
about my lack of experience.

00:04:11.870 --> 00:04:17.029
And I mean, I had operated on
this thesis for a long time.

00:04:17.029 --> 00:04:19.100
But it really went
into overdrive

00:04:19.100 --> 00:04:21.300
when I came here to
New York 18 years ago.

00:04:21.300 --> 00:04:29.420
And even now that I'm, oddly
enough, sort of a traveling

00:04:29.420 --> 00:04:34.550
evangelist for meditation, which
was never in my plan at all--

00:04:34.550 --> 00:04:36.680
even now that I am, I
still actually believe

00:04:36.680 --> 00:04:38.210
the price of security
is insecurity.

00:04:38.210 --> 00:04:41.000
I still think if you're
going to do anything great,

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:42.576
it takes a lot of
work, and stress,

00:04:42.576 --> 00:04:43.700
and plotting, and planning.

00:04:43.700 --> 00:04:45.890
And I do a lot of that.

00:04:49.160 --> 00:04:52.370
Even though I really believe
in the benefits of meditation,

00:04:52.370 --> 00:04:54.470
I'm still as ambitious
as I ever was.

00:04:54.470 --> 00:04:56.720
I not only have my
situation at ABC,

00:04:56.720 --> 00:04:59.930
where I host "Nightline" and
the weekend edition of "Good

00:04:59.930 --> 00:05:02.330
Morning America," but I
have a startup company

00:05:02.330 --> 00:05:08.300
and I think five books
kind of planned in my head

00:05:08.300 --> 00:05:09.380
that I want to do.

00:05:09.380 --> 00:05:12.130
And I have a podcast.

00:05:12.130 --> 00:05:14.850
And I go around giving
speeches and stuff like that.

00:05:14.850 --> 00:05:19.160
So I'm still really ambitious
in some of the same ways

00:05:19.160 --> 00:05:21.320
that I was as a younger guy.

00:05:21.320 --> 00:05:24.560
But I think I'm just less
of an asshole about it.

00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:26.930
I mean, that is really--

00:05:26.930 --> 00:05:28.430
people ask me all
the time, how do I

00:05:28.430 --> 00:05:30.110
know if meditation is working?

00:05:30.110 --> 00:05:32.390
And really the simple
metric is, are you

00:05:32.390 --> 00:05:35.270
less of an asshole to
yourself and others?

00:05:35.270 --> 00:05:36.620
And that's the key.

00:05:36.620 --> 00:05:42.630
Because often the number one
victim of our worst impulses

00:05:42.630 --> 00:05:45.140
is ourselves.

00:05:45.140 --> 00:05:50.690
And so I think that
where meditation helps

00:05:50.690 --> 00:05:54.050
is that I have
learned how to draw

00:05:54.050 --> 00:05:58.790
the line between
useless rumination

00:05:58.790 --> 00:06:00.890
and what I call
constructive anguish.

00:06:00.890 --> 00:06:03.650
There's a certain amount
of plotting and planning

00:06:03.650 --> 00:06:05.991
that makes sense, and
hard work, and stress,

00:06:05.991 --> 00:06:07.740
and banging your head
up against the wall.

00:06:07.740 --> 00:06:09.620
And then it stops making sense.

00:06:09.620 --> 00:06:13.730
And really having increased
self-awareness, which is really

00:06:13.730 --> 00:06:17.240
one of the big
fruits of meditation,

00:06:17.240 --> 00:06:21.260
can help you see, all
right, at this point,

00:06:21.260 --> 00:06:24.530
is this angst useful?

00:06:24.530 --> 00:06:29.210
And learning how to manage
that has made me much more

00:06:29.210 --> 00:06:32.130
effective in my job and
also easier to live with,

00:06:32.130 --> 00:06:35.030
just living with
myself, but also I've

00:06:35.030 --> 00:06:37.629
heard my wife talk about this
many times, just generally

00:06:37.629 --> 00:06:38.670
being less of a shithead.

00:06:38.670 --> 00:06:40.134
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:40.134 --> 00:06:43.070
SPEAKER: Fair.

