So I still love all sorts
of things that I love.

01:01:35.190 --> 01:01:40.540
But it's about hopefully
managing addiction.

01:01:40.540 --> 01:01:42.010
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

01:01:44.960 --> 01:01:47.120
AUDIENCE: Thanks
again for coming in.

01:01:47.120 --> 01:01:50.150
I'm new to the
meditation practice.

01:01:50.150 --> 01:01:52.910
And everything I've read,
including what you said here

01:01:52.910 --> 01:01:56.060
today, the practical
application of meditating,

01:01:56.060 --> 01:02:00.680
it's always recommended to do it
sitting instead of lying down.

01:02:00.680 --> 01:02:02.810
I think I also fall
victim to trying

01:02:02.810 --> 01:02:06.200
to get the most out of something
with the least amount of work.

01:02:06.200 --> 01:02:12.560
And I want to incorporate
meditation in my day-to-day.

01:02:12.560 --> 01:02:14.060
And the easiest
thing I can think of

01:02:14.060 --> 01:02:19.500
is doing it right when
I wake up, lying down.

01:02:19.500 --> 01:02:20.640
Do you not recommend that?

01:02:20.640 --> 01:02:20.760
DAN HARRIS: I think
it's totally fine.

01:02:20.760 --> 01:02:22.426
AUDIENCE: Is there
science behind having

01:02:22.426 --> 01:02:24.800
to do meditation while sitting?

01:02:24.800 --> 01:02:26.120
DAN HARRIS: Totally fine.

01:02:26.120 --> 01:02:28.910
So the Buddha talked
about four ways

01:02:28.910 --> 01:02:31.310
to meditate, four
postures for meditation--

01:02:31.310 --> 01:02:35.060
sitting, standing,
walking, or lying down.

01:02:35.060 --> 01:02:39.620
So you're on the right side of
the angels, as per the Buddha--

01:02:39.620 --> 01:02:41.910
not a bad place to be.

01:02:41.910 --> 01:02:44.480
So I think it's totally fine
to lie down and meditate.

01:02:44.480 --> 01:02:47.880
Your mind's your mind,
whatever posture you're in.

01:02:47.880 --> 01:02:50.690
So if you're training
it, you're training it.

01:02:50.690 --> 01:02:53.330
Now, there are some
schools of meditation,

01:02:53.330 --> 01:02:55.100
especially the Zen
school, that are really

01:02:55.100 --> 01:02:56.720
strict about posture.

01:02:56.720 --> 01:02:59.760
And I think there's
something to that.

01:02:59.760 --> 01:03:02.090
But as a guy who doesn't
like to sit straight,

01:03:02.090 --> 01:03:03.830
can't sit cross-legged,
I'm really

01:03:03.830 --> 01:03:07.369
on the side of the argument
that's what I said before,

01:03:07.369 --> 01:03:09.410
that you're training your
mind, whatever position

01:03:09.410 --> 01:03:10.130
your body's in.

01:03:10.130 --> 01:03:14.684
And that's really where I
would put your attention.

01:03:14.684 --> 01:03:15.350
AUDIENCE: Great.

01:03:15.350 --> 01:03:15.849
Thank you.

01:03:15.849 --> 01:03:18.064
DAN HARRIS: My pleasure.

01:03:18.064 --> 01:03:18.946
AUDIENCE: Hi, Dan.

01:03:18.946 --> 01:03:22.540
A few years ago, you and
Sam Harris were at the Rubin

01:03:22.540 --> 01:03:25.360
and talked about
mindfulness meditation.

01:03:25.360 --> 01:03:26.860
And I think this
was around the time

01:03:26.860 --> 01:03:28.532
you had written "10% Happier."

01:03:28.532 --> 01:03:29.240
DAN HARRIS: Yeah.

01:03:29.240 --> 01:03:32.160
AUDIENCE: And so Sam,
I think jokingly, said,

01:03:32.160 --> 01:03:33.910
I don't want to denigrate
your experience.

01:03:33.910 --> 01:03:37.450
But he talked about
there being a little more

01:03:37.450 --> 01:03:39.220
to mindfulness and
the practice, things

01:03:39.220 --> 01:03:42.190
like the ability to
discover fundamental things

01:03:42.190 --> 01:03:43.990
about the mind,
self-transcendental

01:03:43.990 --> 01:03:44.530
experiences.

01:03:44.530 --> 01:03:47.560
And you brought up how this
is common across religious and

01:03:47.560 --> 01:03:48.400
nonreligious people.

01:03:48.400 --> 01:03:51.760
And you even see it in athletes
who get into a flow state.

01:03:51.760 --> 01:03:55.720
And then he brought up this
idea of the self and the ego

01:03:55.720 --> 01:03:58.090
and how, through meditation,
you can kind of get rid

01:03:58.090 --> 01:03:59.020
of that illusion.

01:03:59.020 --> 01:04:00.440
So I was wondering
if you could--

01:04:00.440 --> 01:04:01.481
what's your take on that?

01:04:01.481 --> 01:04:02.680
Have you moved away--

01:04:02.680 --> 01:04:06.190
or I guess researched more,
discovered more than just

01:04:06.190 --> 01:04:07.894
the utilitarian
aspects of meditation?

01:04:07.894 --> 01:04:09.310
DAN HARRIS: It's
a great question.

01:04:09.310 --> 01:04:11.643
Sam and I just did an event
together in LA the other day

01:04:11.643 --> 01:04:16.210
that's going to post on our
respective podcasts soon.

01:04:16.210 --> 01:04:17.830
It's really a
question of emphasis.

01:04:17.830 --> 01:04:30.970
So Sam is very erudite and is--

01:04:30.970 --> 01:04:32.300
he's a public intellectual.

01:04:32.300 --> 01:04:33.800
That's the way he
thinks of himself.

01:04:33.800 --> 01:04:39.410
And so I am not nearly
as educated as Sam.

01:04:39.410 --> 01:04:41.750
And I'm a TV news anchor.

01:04:41.750 --> 01:04:44.601
So I'm really keeping
things more basic.

01:04:44.601 --> 01:04:46.100
And I'm really
trying to emphasize--

01:04:46.100 --> 01:04:47.895
I speak to folks--

01:04:47.895 --> 01:04:48.770
today, I'm at Google.

01:04:48.770 --> 01:04:51.770
But I'll be in Indiana or
New Orleans or wherever.

01:04:51.770 --> 01:04:55.670
I'm really speaking to all kinds
of people about this-- cops,

01:04:55.670 --> 01:04:58.370
social workers,
celebrities, whatever.

01:04:58.370 --> 01:05:01.040
I want to be able to talk
to everybody in language

01:05:01.040 --> 01:05:02.700
they can understand.

01:05:02.700 --> 01:05:05.484
And so I do.

01:05:05.484 --> 01:05:07.400
And Sam and I have talked
about this publicly.

01:05:07.400 --> 01:05:09.890
I choose to emphasize
certain aspects

01:05:09.890 --> 01:05:12.230
of the practice, primarily two.

01:05:12.230 --> 01:05:13.940
One is focus.

01:05:13.940 --> 01:05:16.490
And the other is mindfulness,
not being yanked around

01:05:16.490 --> 01:05:17.630
by your emotions.

01:05:17.630 --> 01:05:20.060
Of course, Sam is
correct when he

01:05:20.060 --> 01:05:21.980
talks about what is
sometimes referred to

01:05:21.980 --> 01:05:25.370
as the deeper end of the
pool, which is that you start

01:05:25.370 --> 01:05:28.310
to examine the nature of the
self, the nature of who you

01:05:28.310 --> 01:05:30.980
are, the nature
of consciousness.

01:05:30.980 --> 01:05:32.570
All of that stuff
is absolutely real

01:05:32.570 --> 01:05:34.030
and a huge part of my practice.

01:05:34.030 --> 01:05:35.810
And I'm always happy
to talk about it

01:05:35.810 --> 01:05:37.226
because I think,
actually, there's

01:05:37.226 --> 01:05:38.850
nothing more interesting.

01:05:38.850 --> 01:05:41.030
And we talk about it a lot
on my podcast these days.

01:05:41.030 --> 01:05:43.339
But it's not what I lead with.

01:05:43.339 --> 01:05:45.380
Because my audience is
very different from Sam's.

01:05:45.380 --> 01:05:52.670
Sam's is a bunch of really
smart, uptight young men--

01:05:52.670 --> 01:05:55.790
maybe not uptight, but a
lot of really smart guys

01:05:55.790 --> 01:05:57.440
who have opinions about things.

01:05:57.440 --> 01:06:00.380
And I just did this
event with him in LA.

01:06:00.380 --> 01:06:04.010
And they all come.

01:06:04.010 --> 01:06:04.860
And they're great.

01:06:04.860 --> 01:06:07.840
They're super intense
and really smart.

01:06:07.840 --> 01:06:15.380
But so Sam can lead with the
biggest, most esoteric idea

01:06:15.380 --> 01:06:17.780
because that's what
his audience expects.

01:06:17.780 --> 01:06:21.770
But I'm not that smart.

01:06:21.770 --> 01:06:26.960
And I choose really to emphasize
the low-hanging fruit, which

01:06:26.960 --> 01:06:29.900
is why Sam often says, you
should read "10% Happier"

01:06:29.900 --> 01:06:31.710
before you read "Waking Up."

01:06:31.710 --> 01:06:35.330
They work as a
sequence in that way.

01:06:35.330 --> 01:06:38.120
Because I really am
happy splashing around

01:06:38.120 --> 01:06:41.414
in the shallow
end because I am--

01:06:41.414 --> 01:06:43.580
I'm not talking about my
own personal practice here.

01:06:43.580 --> 01:06:46.130
I'm talking about my
public positioning.

01:06:46.130 --> 01:06:47.630
Because I really want--

01:06:47.630 --> 01:06:50.540
I'm sort of at the
wide end of the funnel.

01:06:50.540 --> 01:06:54.440
I want to talk about
the basic human capacity

01:06:54.440 --> 01:06:57.279
to train the mind and
get people in the pool.

01:06:57.279 --> 01:06:58.820
And then in my own
personal practice,

01:06:58.820 --> 01:07:01.020
yeah, I do two hours
a day of meditation.

01:07:01.020 --> 01:07:03.224
I do 10-day silent meditation
retreats one-on-one

01:07:03.224 --> 01:07:04.140
with Joseph Goldstein.

01:07:04.140 --> 01:07:08.240
And all this stuff is the
stuff that I'm obsessed with.

01:07:08.240 --> 01:07:10.400
But it just doesn't
seem to me the way

01:07:10.400 --> 01:07:13.670
to-- the thing to lead with when
I'm trying to get people just

01:07:13.670 --> 01:07:15.997
to do a minute or five
minutes a day of meditation.

01:07:15.997 --> 01:07:17.330
AUDIENCE: Appreciate your work.

01:07:17.330 --> 01:07:17.830
Thanks.

01:07:17.830 --> 01:07:18.180
DAN HARRIS: Thank you.

01:07:18.180 --> 01:07:19.070
Appreciate it.

